\begin_layout Plain Layout
Does 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(t_{0}\right)=0$
\end_inset

? Obviously no.
 So, we do not have UGES.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
END SIDEBAR
\end_layout

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{B}\left(t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 is some constant that might not be the same for every trajectory, but recall
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert N_{B}\left(t\right)\right\Vert \le\gamma_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we write ()
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2}\left\Vert z\left(t\right)\right\Vert ^{2}+P\left(t\right) & \le\left(\frac{1}{2}\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}+\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert \left(\beta n+\gamma_{1}\right)\right)\exp\left(-\lambda_{C}(t-t_{0})\right)\\
\frac{1}{2}\left\Vert z\left(t\right)\right\Vert ^{2} & \le\left(\frac{1}{2}\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}+\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert \left(\beta n+\gamma_{1}\right)\right)\exp\left(-\lambda_{C}(t-t_{0})\right)\\
\left\Vert z\left(t\right)\right\Vert ^{2} & \le\left(\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}+2\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert \left(\beta n+\gamma_{1}\right)\right)\exp\left(-\lambda_{C}(t-t_{0})\right)\\
\left\Vert z\left(t\right)\right\Vert  & \le\underbrace{\sqrt{\left(\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}+2\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert \left(\beta n+\gamma_{1}\right)\right)}}_{W\left(\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert \right)}\exp\left(-\lambda_{C}(t-t_{0})\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left(\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert \right)
\]

\end_inset

is a class 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function, but since there does not exists a single constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{e}\in\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\left(t_{0}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left(\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert \right)\le\gamma_{e}\left\Vert z\left(t_{0}\right)\right\Vert $
\end_inset

, our system is not UGES.
 However, it is GUAS and exponentially convergent at a rate independent
 of initial time and state.
